                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"/>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="illustration">Sixteen miniatures, probably of the mid
                                16th century. Noteworthy features include the form of turban worn by
                                the male characters, the prominence given to tigers in the animal
                                scenes, a fondness for mauve and yellow and non-Persian forms of
                                thrones, crowns, swords, interior architecture, tents, the sun, moon
                                and sky. The spindly trees are also characteristic of Western Indian
                                manuscripts and are without parallel sixteenth-century Persian
                                miniatures. These characteristics seem to point to somewhere in
                                non-Mughal India in the mid-sixteenth century. </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Illumination:</label> Folio <locus
                                    from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears the remnance of a scalloped
                                domed headpiece original to the manuscript, with a horizontal gold
                                cartouche inserted underneath to replace one lost and later
                                replaced, and a finely worked intercolumnar vertical band of floral
                                and palmette scrollwork against a dark ultramarine background.<lb/>
                                <dimensions type="headpiece" unit="mm">
                                    <height>31</height>
                                    <width>65</width>
                                </dimensions><lb/>
                                <dimensions type="cartouche" unit="mm">
                                    <height>22</height>
                                    <width>65</width>
                                </dimensions><lb/>
                                <dimensions type="column" unit="mm">
                                    <height>9</height>
                                    <width>81</width>
                                </dimensions></decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1700" notAfter="1830">
                                <p>Probably rebound in the <origPlace
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                        key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</origPlace> for an
                                    unidentified former owner.</p>
                                <p>Sewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed and traces of
                                    endband threads remaining at the head and tail, now lost.
                                    Covered in full black morocco goatskin
                                        <material>leather</material> over pasteboards, flush-cut,
                                    but without a flap (Type III binding per Déroche). Spine
                                    subsequently rebacked in medium-brown goatskin
                                        <material>leather</material>, with repairs to the upper
                                    corners of the boards exeuted in medium brown
                                        <material>calfskin</material>. The interior now bears
                                    thin-weight, bright blue machine-made paper flyleaves with a
                                    serrated decorative cut hinges applied to the doublures when
                                    last repaired over top of earlier rehinging in red leather,
                                    attesting to repeated repairs to the same binding.</p>
                                <decoNote>Remnants of of gold blocked paper onlays that feature
                                    large lotus blossoms for the scalloped mandorlas, together with
                                    quatrefoil pendants floral scrollwork cornpieces, all since
                                    severely abraded and damaged, with those on the <locus
                                        from="Upper_cover" to="Upper_cover">right board
                                        exterior</locus> delaminated and readhered out of place,
                                    perhas as a result of water damage.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                    <height>196</height>
                                    <width>131</width>
                                    <depth>25</depth>
                                </dimensions></p> 
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In poor condition, with
                                    friable leather and severely damaged decoration, extensive water
                                    stains to the doublures, and weak joints.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin> Completed by <persName role="scribe" key="person_f6495"
                                >Yūsuf</persName>, according to Basil Robinson, in <origPlace
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                                >Western Indian subcontinent</origPlace>, and the illustrations
                                <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1530" to="1570"> date to
                                the mid-16th century CE</origDate>. </origin>
                        <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in
                                Britain remain unclear, an unidentified bookseller offered it for
                                sale as per a pasted catalogue entry found on the <locus
                                    from="Inner_upper_cover" to="Inner_upper_cover">right
                                    doublure</locus>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Formerly part of the collection of the Persian scholar <persName
                                    type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865"
                                    key="person_20108923" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                                    >Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>. Bland’s oriental
                                manuscripts were sold through <persName key="person_5679225"
                                    role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">Bernard Quaritch</persName> in
                                1866 to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880"
                                    key="person_97751058" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                                    >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by <persName key="person_f6379" role="dnr"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands</persName>, on behalf of
                                the John Rylands Library, in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                                    >1901</date> from <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913"
                                    key="person_9985420" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">James
                                    Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
